I've just sold the S&P 500 after staying away in 2018 due to the pains of this trade in 2017. Well aware I may get blown out of the water here so no need to point that out. I feel like Mike McDermott coming back to sit down with Teddy KGB...or I at least want to feel that result!

There was a major crisis. There was an extremely aggressive strategy implemented to manage through the crisis. And now, we need to find our way back to center. I think there's still a ways to go before we get there. The S&P 500 back to the 2015 highs is perfectly reasonable IMHO.

S&P500: Back below 2018 low sets up meaningful top and possible retracement to 2015 high territory. This would amount to a 25-30% decline. While it sounds extreme, when taken in context of the move off the 2009 low, it would look like nothing more than a correction in an uptrend.

It's been a deadly game trying to sell US stocks despite the many red flags including monetary policy normalizations, return of inflation, US protectionism and geopolitical risk. If you are going to sell, my recommendation is to wait to sell into an extended hourly move. SPX

Perhaps...or maybe because of what the market is really thinking...which is higher earnings means higher inflation means higher rates means decidedly less attractive equity market valuations and a big change in the Fed model. Keep an eye on the S&P 500 earnings yield and US tens.
